Author information:

Name: Chen Wang

Date: 2022/03/13

Project title: Does the crackdown in 2021 impact all the pitchers?

Introduction:

What is the research topic from?

In 2021 in MLB, a new foreign-substance crackdown begins: pitchers will be ejected and suspended for using illegal foreign substances to doctor baseballs as Major League Baseball ramps up its enforcement of an area that has been the talk of baseball in recent weeks. It pushed analysts to do data analysis and predicted which players used substances before.

In this regard, analysts found that spin rate drop will be easily detected at the watershed: Normally, if pitcher who causally used substances (such as pine tar) before this year will subsequently has an obvious drop. Hence, the quality of pitching decreased affected the pitcher's stableness in the game.

Pitchers consider that pine tar can help them increase their pitching quality.

Get information from news

I tried to use BeautifulSoup to introduce a piece of news that discussed a pitcher who was famous for its victims after the crackdown.

from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
from urllib.request import urlopen
response= urlopen('https://boston.cbslocal.com/2021/06/24/garrett-richards-spin-rates-drop-drastically-adapt-to-mlb-crackdown-substances/')
soup = BeautifulSoup(response, 'html.parser')
print(soup.prettify())

   <div class="main-white page-block-container and-w-sidebar" id="page-content">
    <header class="" id="page-rubric">
     <div class="banner-title-wrapper">
      <h1 class="title">
       Garrett Richards’ Spin Rates Drop Drastically As Righty Struggles To Adapt To MLB’s Crackdown On Substances
      </h1>
     </div>
    </header>
    <section class="page-columns">
     <section class="page-column three-column" id="article-entry-date-and-tags">
      <div class="column-header">
       <time class="post-date">
        June 24, 2021 at 9:49 am
       </time>
       <div class="column-header-metadata">
        <strong>
         Filed Under:
        </strong>
        <span>
         <a href="https://boston.cbslocal.com/tag/alex-cora/">
          Alex Cora
         </a>
         ,
         <a href="https://boston.cbslocal.com/tag/boston-red-sox/">
          Boston Red Sox
         </a>
         ,
         <a href="https://boston.cbslocal.com/tag/garrett-richards/">
          Garrett Richards
         </a>
         ,
         <a href="https://boston.cbslocal.com/tag/michael-hurley/">
          Michael Hurley
         </a>
         ,
         <a href="https://boston.cbslocal.com/tag/mlb/">
          MLB
         </a>
         ,
         <a href="https://boston.cbslocal.com/tag/sports-news/">
          Sports News
         </a>
         ,
         <a href="https://boston.cbslocal.com/tag/sticky-stuff/">
          Sticky Stuff
         </a>
        </span>
       </div>
      </div>
     </section>
     <section class="page-column and-content-column two-column" id="column_block_18">
      <div class="column-item story" id="main-story">
       <section class="column-item media-type-send2news close-btn" id="featured-media">
        <div class="s2nPlayer k-2L6FI6yB" data-type="float">
        </div>
        <script data-type="s2nScript" src="https://embed.sendtonews.com/player3/embedcode.js?fk=2L6FI6yB&amp;cid=5121&amp;sound=on&amp;floatwidth=430&amp;offsetx=15&amp;offsety=80&amp;floatposition=bottom-right">
        </script>
       </section>
       <div class="main-story-wrapper">
        <p>
         <strong>
          <em>
           By
           <a href="http://boston.cbslocal.com/tag/michael-hurley/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">
            Michael Hurley
           </a>
           , CBS Boston
          </em>
         </strong>
         <p>
          BOSTON (CBS) — When the Red Sox signed Garrett Richards, the veteran right-hander’s exceptional spin rate was considered one of his strongest attributes. Yet now that MLB is cracking down on pitchers using any substances at all to get a grip on baseballs, he’s hit a bit of a rough patch.
         </p>
         <strong style="color: black; float: left; padding-right: 5px;">
          READ MORE:
         </strong>
         <a href="https://boston.cbslocal.com/2022/03/14/sports-psychologist-tom-brady-un-retiring-buccaneers/" style="display: block; margin-bottom: 25px;" target="_blank">
          Sports Psychologist On Tom Brady Un-Retiring: 'It’s His Competitiveness'
         </a>
         <p>
          And that’s putting it mildly.
         </p>
         <p>
          Richards lasted just 1.2 innings on Wednesday night in Tampa, surrendering five runs — four earned — on three hits, a hit batter and four walks while serving up a pair of homers. It was a continuation of a trend for Richards, who is 0-1 with a 9.82 ERA in his last three starts. He’s walked seven batters (with three HBPs) in 11 innings, and opponents have hit .382 with a 1.161 OPS against him during that time.
         </p>
         <p>
          After a rough start to the season, Richards posted a 2.89 ERA in nine starts from mid-April to early June. His ERA has jumped
          <em>
           just about
          </em>
          a full run in the four starts since.
         </p>
         <p>
          Richards’ struggles aligning with MLB paying closer attention to substances is no coincidence. That doesn’t
          <em>
           necessarily
          </em>
          mean that Richards was using Spider Tack or any other illegal substance, but with MLB banning the use of pine tar, rosin, sunscreen and other substances, pitchers are being forced to grip their pitches differently in an effort to try to gain some control of their arsenal. Richards is struggling in that endeavor.
         </p>
         <p>
          “Going through a little transition period right now,” Richards said Wednesday night, per
          <a href="https://www.mlb.com/redsox/news/garrett-richards-struggles-vs-rays" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">
           RedSox.com
          </a>
          . “Changing some grips on some of my pitches, learning new pitches, just trying to figure this whole thing out. Like I said, a little transition period, still determined to get it figured out.”
         </p>
         <strong style="color: black; float: left; padding-right: 5px;">
          READ MORE:
         </strong>
         <a href="https://boston.cbslocal.com/2022/03/14/acton-police-officers-accused-high-school-student/" style="display: block; margin-bottom: 25px;" target="_blank">
          Acton Police Officers On Leave After 'Deeply Disturbing' Allegations By Former High School Student
         </a>
         <p>
          Richards added: “I’m an athlete. I’d like to think I’m going to be able to get over this and figure out a way to get it done.”
         </p>
         <p>
          While spin rates are dropping league-wide, Richards’ spin rate drops on Wednesday were jaw-dropping. Per
          <a href="https://baseballsavant.mlb.com/gamefeed?date=6/23/2021&amp;gamePk=633524&amp;chartType=pitch&amp;legendType=pitchName&amp;playerType=pitcher&amp;inning=&amp;count=&amp;pitchHand=&amp;batSide=&amp;descFilter=&amp;ptFilter=&amp;resultFilter=&amp;hf=playerBreakdown#633524" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">
           Baseball Savant
          </a>
          , his curveball dropped 505 revolutions per minute from his season average. His four-seam fastball dropped 255 RPM, and his slider dropped 210 RPM. He threw just 11 curveballs, only three of which were strikes.
         </p>
         <p>
          While those numbers are staggering, manager Alex Cora said after the game that he’s chiefly concerned about Richards’ fastball, which Cora believes has been cutting over his past three or four starts.
         </p>
         <p>
          “We can talk about breaking ball and slider, but in this league, if your fastball is not playing, you’re gonna have trouble,” Cora said.
         </p>
         <p>
          Richards is, of course, not alone. Gerrit Cole’s sinker dropped 326 RPM on Tuesday night, with his fastball dropping 229 RPM and his slider dropping 216 RPM from his season average, while Trevor Bauer’s numbers continued to drop across the board on Wednesday night. And those are just the marquee names in what is a near-universal issue on mounds across baseball. Tyler Glasnow’s impassioned argument against the banning of
          <em>
           all
          </em>
          substances last week continues to ring loudly as
          <a href="https://boston.cbslocal.com/2021/06/23/mlb-crackdown-sticky-stuff-another-failure-rob-manfred-max-scherzer/" rel="noopener" target="_blank">
           MLB enforces a strict new policy in the middle of a baseball season
          </a>
          .
         </p>
         <p>
          Whether or not the league allows for
          <em>
           some
          </em>
          wiggle room in this area is yet to be seen. For now, pitchers like Richards will be tasked with the difficult challenge of reworking their entire arsenal midseason. It’s certainly not easy, but the playing field appears to be level. It’s now a matter of athletes adapting.
         </p>
         <strong style="color: black; float: left; padding-right: 5px;">
          MORE NEWS:
         </strong>
         <a href="https://boston.cbslocal.com/2022/03/14/sarah-jane-cavanaugh-stolen-valor-marine-medal/" style="display: block; margin-bottom: 25px;" target="_blank">
          Rhode Island Woman Charged With Posing As Wounded Marine Corps Veteran
         </a>
         <p>
          “At the end, we have to compete, right, with what we have, regardless,” Cora said. “Hopefully we can find something during this week and get him ready for his next [start].”
         </p>
        </p>

Read the news and realize that substances attached to the ball can actually improve the quality of pitching, which means the spin rate will also ramp up. However, after the crackdown, some pitchers will not be powerful anymore.

The title is as the below:

story=soup.find('title')
story

<title>Garrett Richards’ Spin Rates Drop Drastically As Righty Struggles To Adapt To MLB’s Crackdown On Substances – CBS Boston</title>
story_date=soup.find('div', attrs = {'class':'main-story-wrapper'}).text
story_date


"By\xa0Michael Hurley, CBS BostonBOSTON (CBS) — When the Red Sox signed Garrett Richards, the veteran right-hander’s exceptional spin rate was considered one of his strongest attributes. Yet now that MLB is cracking down on pitchers using any substances at all to get a grip on baseballs, he’s hit a bit of a rough patch.READ MORE: Sports Psychologist On Tom Brady Un-Retiring: 'It’s His Competitiveness'And that’s putting it mildly.Richards lasted just 1.2 innings on Wednesday night in Tampa, surrendering five runs — four earned — on three hits, a hit batter and four walks while serving up a pair of homers. It was a continuation of a trend for Richards, who is 0-1 with a 9.82 ERA in his last three starts. He’s walked seven batters (with three HBPs) in 11 innings, and opponents have hit .382 with a 1.161 OPS against him during that time.After a rough start to the season, Richards posted a 2.89 ERA in nine starts from mid-April to early June. His ERA has jumped\xa0just about\xa0a full run in the four starts since.Richards’ struggles aligning with MLB paying closer attention to substances is no coincidence. That doesn’t necessarily mean that Richards was using Spider Tack or any other illegal substance, but with MLB banning the use of pine tar, rosin, sunscreen and other substances, pitchers are being forced to grip their pitches differently in an effort to try to gain some control of their arsenal. Richards is struggling in that endeavor.“Going through a little transition period right now,” Richards said Wednesday night, per RedSox.com. “Changing some grips on some of my pitches, learning new pitches, just trying to figure this whole thing out. Like I said, a little transition period, still determined to get it figured out.”READ MORE: Acton Police Officers On Leave After 'Deeply Disturbing' Allegations By Former High School StudentRichards added: “I’m an athlete. I’d like to think I’m going to be able to get over this and figure out a way to get it done.”While spin rates are dropping league-wide, Richards’ spin rate drops on Wednesday were jaw-dropping. Per Baseball Savant, his curveball dropped 505 revolutions per minute from his season average. His four-seam fastball dropped 255 RPM, and his slider dropped 210 RPM. He threw just 11 curveballs, only three of which were strikes.While those numbers are staggering, manager Alex Cora said after the game that he’s chiefly concerned about Richards’ fastball, which Cora believes has been cutting over his past three or four starts.“We can talk about breaking ball and slider, but in this league, if your fastball is not playing, you’re gonna have trouble,” Cora said.Richards is, of course, not alone. Gerrit Cole’s sinker dropped 326 RPM on Tuesday night, with his fastball dropping 229 RPM and his slider dropping 216 RPM from his season average, while Trevor Bauer’s numbers continued to drop across the board on Wednesday night. And those are just the marquee names in what is a near-universal issue on mounds across baseball. Tyler Glasnow’s impassioned argument against the banning of all substances last week continues to ring loudly as MLB enforces a strict new policy in the middle of a baseball season.Whether or not the league allows for\xa0some\xa0wiggle room in this area is yet to be seen. For now, pitchers like Richards will be tasked with the difficult challenge of reworking their entire arsenal midseason. It’s certainly not easy, but the playing field appears to be level. It’s now a matter of athletes adapting.MORE NEWS: Rhode Island Woman Charged With Posing As Wounded Marine Corps Veteran“At the end, we have to compete, right, with what we have, regardless,” Cora said. “Hopefully we can find something during this week and get him ready for his next [start].”\n\n\n\n\n\n\n"

We get the information that someone's pitching has an obvious drop. When I detailed to check the news, I know this man is Garrett Richards.

Methods description:

Chapter 1: Does the pine tar or any substances will actually affect the quality?

  • Use Garrett Richards as an example, point out before and after the crackdown if they have a difference (normal distribution).
  • Use correlation function to check if other parameters have an obvious correlation
  • Use the histogram to roughly check if data is a normal distribution (no right tail, left tail, or bimodal distribution)
  • Use QQ-lot, to check if it is the normal distribution
  • Use T-test(Levene test), to check P-value if it is >0.05

In Changeup, Check Pearson R2: if other parameters were predictable from spin rate to speed:

I found speed actually has the highest correlation from other parameters (Vy0 is high, but Vy0 means the velocity of y-axis, means if the speed has a high R2, the Vx0 or Vy0 or Vz0 will also be high)

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

Even the dataset is only 19 counts, it still can tell me it is not a normal distribution. Let's check the QQ plot. the result tells me there is an bimodal distribution, which is not a normal distribution

from scipy import stats
stats.probplot(diff_res, plot=plt, dist='norm');

Calculate the shapiro test p-value<0.05, it's not a normal distribution (actually, it's a bimodal distribution)

stats.shapiro(diff_res)

ShapiroResult(statistic=0.9057035446166992, pvalue=4.8623792825012366e-21)

				espn.ads.loadGPT();
			}

			if (espnAdsConfig.prebidAdConfig && espnAdsConfig.prebidAdConfig.usePrebidBids) {
				

				// Load prebid.js for AppNexus
				(function() {
					var d = document, pbs = d.createElement('script'), pro = d.location.protocol;
					pbs.type = 'text/javascript';
					pbs.src = ((pro === 'https:') ? 'https' : 'http') + '://a.espncdn.com/prod/scripts/prebid4.35.0.js';
					var target = document.getElementsByTagName('head')[0];
					target.insertBefore(pbs, target.firstChild);
				})();
			}

			espn.ads.configPre = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(espnAdsConfig));
		})();
            </script>

         <header class="article-header">
          <h1>
           Sources: New York Mets, Max Scherzer agree to three-year, $130 million contract
          </h1>
         </header>
         <ul class="article-social horizontal" data-id="32745735" data-name="Sources%3A%20New%20York%20Mets,%20Max%20Scherzer%20agree%20to%20three%2Dyear,%20%24130%20million%20contract" data-src="https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/32745735" data-type="article">

         <div class="article-body">
          <div class="article-meta">
           <span class="timestamp" data-behavior="date_time" data-date="2021-11-29T18:26:00Z">
            <span data-dateformat="date1">
             Nov 29, 2021

           <li>

            </a>

            <a class="btn-social icon-font-before icon-facebook-messenger-solid-before vertical" data-social-tool="facebookMessenger" data-social-type="vertical" href="http://facebook.com/dialog/send?link=https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/32745735&amp;next=https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/32745735&amp;app_id=116656161708917">
             Facebook Messenger
            </a>
           </li>
           <li>
            <a class="btn-social icon-font-before icon-pinterest-solid-before vertical" data-social-tool="pinterest" data-social-type="vertical" href="https://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.espn.com%2Fmlb%2Fstory%2F_%2Fid%2F32745735%2Fsources%2Dnew%2Dyork%2Dmets%2Dmax%2Dscherzer%2Dfinalizing%2D3%2Dyear%2Ddeal&amp;description=Sources%3A+New+York+Mets%2C+Max+Scherzer+agree+to+three-year%2C+%24130+million+contract&amp;media=https%3A%2F%2Fa.espncdn.com%2Fphoto%2F2021%2F1018%2Fr924392_2_1296x729_16-9.jpg">

            </a>

           <li class="internal send-email">
            <a class="page-action email" data-route="false" data-social-tool="email" data-social-type="vertical" href="mailto:?subject=Sources%3A%20New%20York%20Mets,%20Max%20Scherzer%20agree%20to%20three%2Dyear,%20%24130%20million%20contract&amp;body=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.espn.com%2Fmlb%2Fstory%2F_%2Fid%2F32745735">
             Email
            </a>
           </li>
           <li class="internal first">
            <a class="btn-social page-action print icon-font-before icon-print-solid-before vertical" data-social-tool="print" data-social-type="vertical" href="https://www.espn.com/espn/print?id=32745735">
             print
            </a>
           </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
           Star right-hander
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/28976/max-scherzer">
            Max Scherzer
           </a>
           and the
           <a href="/mlb/team/_/name/nym/new-york-mets">
            New York Mets
           </a>
           have agreed to a three-year, $130 million contract, sources familiar with the situation told ESPN's Jeff Passan.
          </p>
          <p>
           Scherzer can opt out of the contract after the second season of the deal, the sources said.
          </p>
          <p>
           The $43.33 million average annual salary of the deal sets a record, surpassing the $36 million
           <a href="/mlb/team/_/name/nyy/new-york-yankees">
            New York Yankees
           </a>
           pitcher
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/32081/gerrit-cole">
            Gerrit Cole
           </a>
           is averaging after signing a nine-year, $324 million contract in 2019.
          </p>
          <p>
           Scherzer, 37, becomes the oldest player in MLB history to sign a $100 million contract, according to ESPN Stats &amp; Information. Kevin Brown was 33 when he signed the first $100 million deal in MLB history in 1998.
          </p>
          <p>
           The Mets
           <a href="/mlb/story/_/id/32721619/source-new-york-mets-infielder-eduardo-escobar-agree-2-year-20-million-deal">
            have gone on a spending spree
           </a>
           over the weekend, signing center fielder
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/30830/starling-marte">
            Starling Marte
           </a>
           , infielder
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/30272/eduardo-escobar">
            Eduardo Escobar
           </a>
           and outfielder
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/31670/mark-canha">
            Mark Canha
           </a>
           to deals worth a combined $124.5 million.
          </p>
          <p>
           And after seeing starters
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/31730/noah-syndergaard">
            Noah Syndergaard
           </a>
           and
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/33106/steven-matz">
            Steven Matz
           </a>
           sign with other clubs in the past two weeks, new owner Steve Cohen wasn't going to be denied one of the best pitchers available in Scherzer.
          </p>
          <aside class="inline editorial float-r" data-behavior="article_related">
           <h1>
            Editor's Picks
           </h1>
           <ul>
            <li>
             <a class="img-link" href="/mlb/insider/story/_/id/32745682/max-scherzer-megadeal-changes-narrative-new-york-mets" name="&amp;lpos=story:editorspicks:inline:1">

             </a>
             <h2>
              <a href="/mlb/insider/story/_/id/32745682/max-scherzer-megadeal-changes-narrative-new-york-mets" name="&amp;lpos=story:editorspicks:inline:1">
               What dy$function? Mets' megadeal for Scherzer proves money changes everything
              </a>

               </span>

               </span>
              </div>
             </h2>
            </li>
            <li>
             <a class="img-link" href="/fantasy/baseball/insider/story/_/id/32745816/what-happens-max-scherzer-fantasy-value-flushing" name="&amp;lpos=story:editorspicks:inline:2">
              <img height="65" src="https://a.espncdn.com/combiner/i?img=/photo/2021/1129/r944231_1296x1296_1-1.jpg&amp;w=130&amp;h=130&amp;scale=crop&amp;location=center" width="65"/>
             </a>
             <h2>
              <a href="/fantasy/baseball/insider/story/_/id/32745816/what-happens-max-scherzer-fantasy-value-flushing" name="&amp;lpos=story:editorspicks:inline:2">
               What happens to Max Scherzer's fantasy value in Flushing?
              </a>
              <div class="editorial--metadata icon-espnplus-before">
               <span class="timestamp">
                106d
               </span>
               <span class="author">
                Tristan H. Cockcroft
               </span>
              </div>
             </h2>
            </li>
            <li>
             <a class="img-link" href="/mlb/insider/story/_/id/32744498/is-mlb-lockout-coming-free-agency-freeze-jeff-passan-answers-20-burning-questions" name="&amp;lpos=story:editorspicks:inline:3">
              <img height="65" src="https://a.espncdn.com/combiner/i?img=/photo/2021/1129/r944168_1296x1296_1-1.jpg&amp;w=130&amp;h=130&amp;scale=crop&amp;location=center" width="65"/>
             </a>
             <h2>
              <a href="/mlb/insider/story/_/id/32744498/is-mlb-lockout-coming-free-agency-freeze-jeff-passan-answers-20-burning-questions" name="&amp;lpos=story:editorspicks:inline:3">
               Is an MLB lockout coming? Will free agency freeze? Jeff Passan answers 20 burning questions
              </a>
              <div class="editorial--metadata icon-espnplus-before">
               <span class="timestamp">
                105d
               </span>
               <span class="author">
                Jeff Passan
               </span>
              </div>
             </h2>
            </li>
           </ul>
           <div class="button button-alt sm btn-related">
            2 Related
           </div>
          </aside>
          <p>
           Scherzer joins a Mets rotation fronted by two-time National League Cy Young Award winner
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/32796/jacob-degrom">
            Jacob deGrom
           </a>
           , who didn't pitch after July 7 last season because of concerns with his elbow -- although a late-season MRI showed that his elbow was healthy.
          </p>
          <p>
           Scherzer, a three-time Cy Young Award winner, was among the preeminent pitchers of the 2010s -- along with
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/6341/justin-verlander">
            Justin Verlander
           </a>
           and
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/28963/clayton-kershaw">
            Clayton Kershaw
           </a>
           -- and has rolled his dominance into the 2020s.
          </p>
          <p>
           In 2021, during his age-36 season, Scherzer went 15-4 with a 2.46 ERA in 179⅓ innings for the
           <a href="/mlb/team/_/name/wsh/washington-nationals">
            Washington Nationals
           </a>
           and the
           <a href="/mlb/team/_/name/lad/los-angeles-dodgers">
            Los Angeles Dodgers
           </a>
           , striking out 236 batters and walking only 36. He ultimately finished third in NL Cy Young Award voting, marking the eighth time in the past nine years he has finished within the top five.
          </p>
          <p>
           During that stretch, which dates back to 2013, Scherzer has posted a 2.82 ERA while averaging 15 wins and 192 innings per season (even though the 2020 season was shortened to 60 games because of the coronavirus pandemic). His 51.2 FanGraphs WAR since then leads all pitchers.
          </p>
          <p>
           Scherzer was originally the 11th overall pick in the 2006 draft by the
           <a href="/mlb/team/_/name/ari/arizona-diamondbacks">
            Arizona Diamondbacks
           </a>
           , who flipped him to the
           <a href="/mlb/team/_/name/det/detroit-tigers">
            Detroit Tigers
           </a>
           three years later in a major three-team trade that saw Curtis Granderson, Edwin Jackson and
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/28864/ian-kennedy">
            Ian Kennedy
           </a>
           , among others, switch teams.
          </p>
          <p>
           In Detroit, Scherzer formed a devastating duo with Verlander on perennial playoff teams that often fell just short of a championship. He joined the Nationals on a seven-year, $210 million free-agent deal in January of 2015 and somehow outperformed his contract over the course of six-plus seasons, a highly impressive run that culminated in winning the 2019 World Series.
          </p>
          <p>
           The Dodgers acquired Scherzer alongside middle infielder
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/33710/trea-turner">
            Trea Turner
           </a>
           in late July 2020 in exchange for their two best remaining prospects, catcher
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/38827/keibert-ruiz">
            Keibert Ruiz
           </a>
           and pitcher
           <a href="https://www.espn.com/mlb/player/_/id/41165/josiah-gray">
            Josiah Gray
           </a>
           . Scherzer dominated initially, with a 0.78 ERA through his first nine starts, but his arm was slow to recover from being used in the ninth inning of Game 5 of the National League Division Series against the
           <a href="/mlb/team/_/name/sf/san-francisco-giants">
            San Francisco Giants
           </a>
           .
          </p>
          <div class="ad-300">
           <div class="ad-center">
            <div class="ad-slot ad-slot-incontent2 ad-wrapper" data-independent="true" data-slot-kvps="pos=incontent2" data-slot-type="incontent2">
            </div>
           </div>
          </div>
          <p>
           Scherzer languished through Game 2 of the National League Championship Series against the
           <a href="/mlb/team/_/name/atl/atlanta-braves">
            Atlanta Braves
           </a>
           , later saying his arm was still tired from his relief appearance three days earlier. He was initially scheduled to start again in Game 6 but was pushed back to Game 7 because of lingering soreness -- then watched the Dodgers get eliminated in Game 6, abruptly ending another dominant Scherzer season.
          </p>
          <p>
           Scherzer is 190-97 with a 3.16 ERA in 14 major league seasons. He has 3,020 strikeouts, which ranks 18th on the all-time list.
          </p>
          <p>
           The addition of Scherzer moved the Mets' odds at Caesars Sportsbook to win the 2022 World Series to 14-1, tied for the sixth-shortest odds to win the championship.
          </p>
          <p>
           <i>
            ESPN's Alden Gonzalez contributed to this report.
           </i>
          </p>

soup_Scherzer.find('title')

<title>Sources - New York Mets, Max Scherzer agree to three-year, $130 million contract</title>
for i in soup_Scherzer.find_all('p'):
    print(i.text)


Star right-hander Max Scherzer and the New York Mets have agreed to a three-year, $130 million contract, sources familiar with the situation told ESPN's Jeff Passan.
Scherzer can opt out of the contract after the second season of the deal, the sources said.
The $43.33 million average annual salary of the deal sets a record, surpassing the $36 million New York Yankees pitcher Gerrit Cole is averaging after signing a nine-year, $324 million contract in 2019.
Scherzer, 37, becomes the oldest player in MLB history to sign a $100 million contract, according to ESPN Stats & Information. Kevin Brown was 33 when he signed the first $100 million deal in MLB history in 1998.
The Mets have gone on a spending spree over the weekend, signing center fielder Starling Marte, infielder Eduardo Escobar and outfielder Mark Canha to deals worth a combined $124.5 million.
And after seeing starters Noah Syndergaard and Steven Matz sign with other clubs in the past two weeks, new owner Steve Cohen wasn't going to be denied one of the best pitchers available in Scherzer.
Scherzer joins a Mets rotation fronted by two-time National League Cy Young Award winner Jacob deGrom, who didn't pitch after July 7 last season because of concerns with his elbow -- although a late-season MRI showed that his elbow was healthy.
Scherzer, a three-time Cy Young Award winner, was among the preeminent pitchers of the 2010s -- along with Justin Verlander and Clayton Kershaw -- and has rolled his dominance into the 2020s.
In 2021, during his age-36 season, Scherzer went 15-4 with a 2.46 ERA in 179⅓ innings for the Washington Nationals and the Los Angeles Dodgers, striking out 236 batters and walking only 36. He ultimately finished third in NL Cy Young Award voting, marking the eighth time in the past nine years he has finished within the top five.
During that stretch, which dates back to 2013, Scherzer has posted a 2.82 ERA while averaging 15 wins and 192 innings per season (even though the 2020 season was shortened to 60 games because of the coronavirus pandemic). His 51.2 FanGraphs WAR since then leads all pitchers.
Scherzer was originally the 11th overall pick in the 2006 draft by the Arizona Diamondbacks, who flipped him to the Detroit Tigers three years later in a major three-team trade that saw Curtis Granderson, Edwin Jackson and Ian Kennedy, among others, switch teams.
In Detroit, Scherzer formed a devastating duo with Verlander on perennial playoff teams that often fell just short of a championship. He joined the Nationals on a seven-year, $210 million free-agent deal in January of 2015 and somehow outperformed his contract over the course of six-plus seasons, a highly impressive run that culminated in winning the 2019 World Series.
The Dodgers acquired Scherzer alongside middle infielder Trea Turner in late July 2020 in exchange for their two best remaining prospects, catcher Keibert Ruiz and pitcher Josiah Gray. Scherzer dominated initially, with a 0.78 ERA through his first nine starts, but his arm was slow to recover from being used in the ninth inning of Game 5 of the National League Division Series against the San Francisco Giants.
Scherzer languished through Game 2 of the National League Championship Series against the Atlanta Braves, later saying his arm was still tired from his relief appearance three days earlier. He was initially scheduled to start again in Game 6 but was pushed back to Game 7 because of lingering soreness -- then watched the Dodgers get eliminated in Game 6, abruptly ending another dominant Scherzer season.
Scherzer is 190-97 with a 3.16 ERA in 14 major league seasons. He has 3,020 strikeouts, which ranks 18th on the all-time list.
The addition of Scherzer moved the Mets' odds at Caesars Sportsbook to win the 2022 World Series to 14-1, tied for the sixth-shortest odds to win the championship.
ESPN's Alden Gonzalez contributed to this report.
